stylometry: When looking at an output from @Risk, it mainly focues on showing the user the profit comparisons.  A company would be looking for profit, standard deviation, mean, etc. when trying to make a decision about how many calendars to order.  Demand needs to be met, so trying to find the profit maximization is key.  The right amount of calendars need to be ordered in order to better the company.  When looking at @risk, which shows the distribution of results and not just one, factors such as profit, and standard deviation can be compared in order to place the best possible order.
